John Edward: Language skills crucial for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain outstanding academic results and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, which are only strengthened by individual and collective advances in sport, art, music and other community engagement.
With up to 30 000 pupils in Scotland, schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), seek to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement custom curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought-after subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students studying foreign languages received a final sample of Higher Grade.
Data, collected from the SCIS 74 member schools, showed that 72 per cent of students studying tangerine received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 per cent of students studying German, 69 per cent of students studying French and 63 per cent of students studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subject choices are now considered as important as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in curricula in independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that employers found it difficult to fill their vacancies for various reasons, with 17% attributed to a lack of language skills.
Having said that, language skills become all the more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills become essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of their career choices, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adult Britons published by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent replied that they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that came up in total in a two-digit percentage (15%).
That is why it is so important to invest in language teaching for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be most important for the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and get them with the skills to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly language that continues to be crucial for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really should be regarded as "international communication capacity".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
Il faut bien le fere.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
