The ship should have joined the fleet already in 2014, but the problems that arose after delivery were disastrous for the ambitious project.
The four ships in Baden-Wuertemberg class ordered by the fleet in 2007 will replace the ageing Bremen frigates.
They will contain a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and marine missiles, as well as certain stealth techniques, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to station the newest frigates for up to two years without contact with home ports.
But continuous delays mean that the groundbreaking warships - which allow Germany to project power abroad - are already obsolete when they come into operation, writes Die Zeit.
The fateful F125 frigate created headlines last year, when the German fleet officially refused to put the ship into operation and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time that the fleet returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
A little was known about the causes of the return, but German media indicated a number of important "software and hardware errors" that made the warship useless if used on a combat mission.
Weaknesses in the software were particularly important because ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class will be run by a staff of about 120 sailors - only half of the crew of older frigates in the Bremen class.
It was also found that the ship has a significant excess weight, which leads to reduced performance and limits the marine’s ability to perform future upgrades.
The 7 000 tonnes of heavy "Rheinland-Pfalz" is assumed to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Apart from faulty hardware, the entire project price tag - including crew training - also becomes a problem.
