The National Trust eavesdrops to the secret lives of bats
New research carried out on a property in the highlands of Scotland aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
We hope that the results will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow South and Dwarf Pipestrell as well as brown long-eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in important locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and the species that do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, such as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from house treasures.
Bats aren't actually blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, check nests, and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Three Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager David Thompson says that the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here at Three, we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and a variety of favorable habitats.
But there is much about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand more about what they need to enjoy.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before performing maintenance in real estate, as it is possible that accidental destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young, and possibly wipe out an entire population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we do not know how their populations are."
